{{about|the Luxembourgish statesman and industrialist|the American cultural historian|Leon Claire Metz}} {{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = |name = Charles-Léon Metz |honorific-suffix = |image = |alt = |caption = |office1 = Member of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] for [[Esch-sur-Alzette (Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg constituency)|Esch-sur-Alzette]] |term_start1 = 1875 |term_end1 = 1918 |birth_date = 1 November 1842 |birth_place = [[Berbourg]] |death_date = 25 June 1928 |death_place = [[Esch-sur-Alzette]] |restingplace = |restingplacecoordinates = |nationality = [[Luxembourg]]ish |party = |otherparty = |spouse = |children = |residence = |alma_mater = |occupation = [[Entrepreneur]] ([[steel industry|steel]]) |religion = |signature = |signature_alt = |footnotes = }} '''Charles-Léon Metz''' (1 November 1842 – 25 June 1928)<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 400</ref> was a [[Luxembourg]]ish politician and industrialist. He was a member of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] for forty-three years (1875–1918), and served as [[Mayor of Esch-sur-Alzette]] from 1906 to 1909.
The son of [[Auguste Metz]] and Petronille Laeis, he was a member of the prominent [[Metz family]], and he entered the family business of metallurgy. He was first elected to the [[Esch-sur-Alzette communal council|communal council]] of [[Esch-sur-Alzette]] in 1873, and served for four years before becoming an ''[[Échevin (Luxembourg)|échevin]]'' on 16 January 1877.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 402</ref> He was also elected to the national [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]] as a liberal on 14 October 1875, representing [[Esch-sur-Alzette (canton)|Esch-sur-Alzette]].<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 404</ref> Although a liberal, he was a traditionalist, a practising [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]], and had close ties to the religious establishment in Esch.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 406</ref>
Metz was named Mayor of Esch on 22 October 1906, which was renewed on 28 December 1908. During his tenure as mayor, the most important decision was the [[Communes of Luxembourg|commune]]'s purchase of the Forest of Esch, and its replacement with new steel mills, in the district of [[Belval, Luxembourg|Belval]].<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 403</ref> Although Metz won re-election in the [[Luxembourgian communal elections, 1909|1909 communal elections]], he decided to resign on 28 November 1909, having served three years as mayor.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 404</ref>
Metz lost in his bid to be reelected to the Chamber of Deputies in the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1918|1918 election]],<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 407</ref> and withdrew from public life.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 408</ref> He died on 25 June 1928.<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 410</ref>
==Decorations== Metz was awarded a number of decorations:<ref>Mersch (1963), p. 409–10</ref>
* Commander, [[Order of the Oak Crown]] (Luxembourg) * Commander, [[Order of Adolphe of Nassau]] (Luxembourg) * Commander, [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Order of the Crown]] (Belgium) * Commander, [[Order of the Crown of Italy|Order of the Crown]] (Italy) * Knight (1st class), [[Order of the White Falcon]] ([[Saxe-Weimar-Eisenach]])
