{{Infobox person |name = Philippe Suchard |image = Philippe Suchard.jpg |caption = |birth_date = 9 October 1797 |birth_place = [[Boudry]], [[Switzerland]] |death_date = {{d-da|14 January 1884|9 October 1797}} |death_place = [[Neuchâtel]], [[Switzerland]] |other_names = |known_for = Creator of [[Milka]] |occupation = chocolatier |nationality = Swiss }}
'''Philippe Suchard''' (9 October 1797 &ndash; 14 January 1884) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[chocolatier]] and [[industrialist]].
==Biography== Suchard was born in 1797 in [[Boudry]]. According to the [[memoirs]] of his sister Rosalie, he became aware of the potentialities of chocolate manufacturing as an industry at the very early age of about twelve.<ref name=swissworld>{{cite web | url = http://www.swissworld.org/en/people/portraits_chocolate_makers/philippe_suchard/ | title = Philippe Suchard biography | accessdate=2008-09-07}}</ref> To fulfill his dream, six years later he started as an apprentice in his brother Frédéric's ''[[Konditorei]]'' in [[Bern]]. In 1824 he left Switzerland to visit the [[United States]]. At the end of the year he returned and opened a confectioner's business in Neuchâtel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finedarkchocolate.com/Swiss_Chocolate/Philippe_Suchard.asp |title=Philippe Suchard (1797&ndash;1884), Swiss Master Chocolate Maker |accessdate=2009-09-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081114022927/http://www.finedarkchocolate.com/Swiss_Chocolate/PHILIPPE_SUCHARD.asp |archivedate=November 14, 2008 }}</ref> In 1826, Suchard opened the factory of Chocolat Suchard in [[Serrières, Neuchâtel|Serrières]]. He used [[hydropower]] of the nearby river to run the mills in his two-man factory. Suchard used a grinding mill consisting of a heated [[granite]] plate, and several granite rollers moving forwards and backwards. This design is still used to grind [[Cocoa bean|cocoa]] paste.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://brandstell.com/index.php?cmd=news_full_text&type=arch&id=1026&lang=en | title = Milka | accessdate = 2008-09-07 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110708091006/http://brandstell.com/index.php?cmd=news_full_text&type=arch&id=1026&lang=en | archivedate = 2011-07-08 | df = }}</ref>
Chocolate was not cheap or a product for everybody. Suchard struggled financially early in his career as a chocolatier. His success came in 1842, with a bulk order from [[Frederick William IV of Prussia|Frederick William IV, king of Prussia]], who was also the prince of [[Neuchâtel]]. This triggered a boom and soon his chocolates won prizes at the London [[Great Exhibition of 1851]] and the Paris [[Exposition Universelle (1855)|Universal Exposition of 1855]]. He opened his first factory abroad in 1880 in [[Lörrach]], [[Germany]], becoming the first to do so. The unusual purple color of the chocolate packaging was selected by Suchard, who believed it would be unique among chocolate packaging.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://brandstell.com/index.php?cmd=news_full_text&type=arch&id=1027&lang=en | title = Brand News | accessdate = 2008-09-07 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110708091508/http://brandstell.com/index.php?cmd=news_full_text&type=arch&id=1027&lang=en | archivedate = 2011-07-08 | df = }}</ref> By the end of the 19th century, Suchard had become the largest chocolate producer.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chocosuisse.ch/page/2_1_geschichte-en.html | title = From cocoa to chocolate | accessdate=2008-09-07 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501145719/http://www.chocosuisse.ch/page/2_1_geschichte-en.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-05-01}}</ref> Seventeen years after his death in 1884 in Neuchâtel, his company produced the famous [[Milka]] chocolate for the Swiss market.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.theobroma-cacao.de/wissen/geschichte/personen/philippe-suchard/ | title = Lebenslauf von Philippe Suchard | accessdate=2008-09-07}}</ref> After his death, his daughter Eugénie Suchard and her husband Karl Russ-Suchard, took over the functioning of his factory.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.le-musee.ch/500-Animations/veillee050608.htm | title = Philippe Suchard: de Boudry à l'Orient du Minaret | accessdate=2008-09-09| language = French}}</ref> Nowadays the factory belongs to the [[Mondelez]] group and production has been moved to the [[Toblerone]] factory in Bern.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kraftfoods.ch/kraft/page?siteid=kraft-prd&locale=chde1&PagecRef=2505&Mid=2505 | title= Süsse Fakten zu Milka, Toblerone und Suchard | language = German | accessdate = 2008-09-10}}</ref>
==Other interests== [[Image:Mosquee-Neuchatel-Negative0-13-11A(1).jpg|250px|right|thumb|Suchard's house in Neuchâtel built in 1865 by architect [[Louis-Daniel Perrier]], inspired by his trip to the [[Middle East]]]] Suchard was not only a chocolatier but also had interest in other areas. In 1834 he introduced and captained the first [[steamboat|steamer]], ''Industriel'', on [[Lake Neuchâtel]]. He also tried introducing [[silkworm]] culture in Switzerland in 1837, but the silkworms were destroyed during an epidemic in 1843. His interest in managing river water and controlling floods led to the sinking of the water level in Lake Neuchâtel. The lowered lake shoreline revealed the [[Celts|Celtic]] settlement of [[La Tène]] dating back to around 450 BC.<ref name=swissworld />
