'''Sir Samuel Chapman''' (1859 &ndash; 29 April 1947) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] businessman and [[Unionist Party (Scotland)|Scottish Unionist Party]] politician from [[Perthshire]].

He unsuccessfully contested the [[Perth (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth]] constituency in [[United Kingdom general election, 1906|1906]] and [[United Kingdom general election, January 1910|January 1910]], and the [[Greenock (UK Parliament constituency)|Greenock]] constituency in [[United Kingdom general election, December 1910|December 1910]] and in [[United Kingdom general election, 1918|1918]], but was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Edinburgh South (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh South]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1922|1922 general election]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32775|page=8712|date=8 December 1922}}</ref> (he was chosen as Unionist candidate for that seat over [[Katharine Stewart-Murray, Duchess of Atholl]]<ref>Knox, William. ''The Lives of Scottish Women: Women and Scottish Society, 1800-1980'' Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 2006; p. 168</ref>) and held the seat<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32897|page=368|date=11 January 1924}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32996|page=8534|date=25 November 1924}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33508|page=4117|date=21 June 1929}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33769|page=7146|date=6 November 1931}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34223|page=7506|date=26 November 1935}}</ref> until he stepped down at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1945|1945 general election]].

He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the 1920 [[New Year Honours]], for "Valuable War work, especially in connection with the Perth and Perthshire Prisoners of War Fund; Public and Local services".<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31712|supp=y|page=2|date=30 December 1919}}</ref>

